<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="10" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
DESCRIPTION.—Form: Generally as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1871" box="[1955,2101,1296,1333]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gruti">
X. 
<emphasis box="[2021,2101,1296,1332]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">gruti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except narrower, with more highly convex elytra, and with much smaller eyes. Color as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates Pronotum" authorityYear="1884" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ampliatus">
<emphasis box="[1983,2013,1387,1424]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[2040,2104,1388,1424]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">ampliatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but easily distinguished from that species by the narrower explanations of the pronotum 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2041,2101,1479,1516]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">and</emphasis>
elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[1280,1390,1574,1610]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Color:</emphasis>
Head and body rufous; pronotum and elytra moderately iridescent; appendages testaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[1278,1385,1667,1703]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Head:</emphasis>
Narrow between eyes; frontal furrows deeply and broadly impressed; eyes moderately 
<emphasis box="[1243,1323,1758,1795]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">large</emphasis>
and prominent; mouthparts as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 4-6" captionStartId="14.[524,628,1481,1512]" captionTargetBox="[286,2110,491,1467]" captionText="FIGURES 4-6.—Xystosomus strigosus Bates, male, from Nova Teutonia, Brazil: 4, maxilla, left side, dorsal aspect; 5, labium, right side, ventral aspect; 6, anterior left leg, posterior aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3828539" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3828539/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Figures 4, 5</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1491,1643,1852,1889]" captionStart="FIGURES 7-21" captionStartId="16.[518,621,2410,2440]" captionTargetBox="[362,2050,505,2326]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 7-21.—Pronotum, dorsal aspect: 7, Xystosomus ampliatus, female, Hamburg Farm, Costa Rica; 8, X. nigripalpis, female, Barro Colorado Island, Panama; 9, X. strigosus, female, Rio Parahyba, Brazil; 10, X. iris, female, Cochabamba, Bolivia; 11, X. sculpticollis, female, Teffe, Brazil; 12, X. negrei, male, Rancho Grande, Venezuela; 13, X. aetholius, female, Cochabamba, Bolivia; 14, X. anterocostis, Hamburg Farm, Costa Rica; 15, X. sublaevis, male, Rio Banano, Costa Rica; 16, X. sulcicostis, female, Volcan de Chiriqu!, Panama; 17, X. apicisulcatus, female, Minas, Brazil; 18, X. batesi, female, Petr6polis, Brazil; 19, X. seriatus, female, Nova Teutonia, Brazil; 20, X. ovatulus, female, Caraca, Brazil; 21, X. grossipunctatus, female, Caraca, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3828541" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3828541/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Figure 9</figureCitation>
): Less transverse than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1871" box="[1244,1381,1897,1934]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gruti">
<emphasis box="[1244,1274,1897,1934]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">X</emphasis>
. gruti
</taxonomicName>
(W/L, x 1.51; range, 1.42-1.64; 5 specimens) and with less explanate side margins, otherwise similar; anterior leg as in 
<figureCitation box="[1773,1915,1989,2026]" captionStart="FIGURES 4-6" captionStartId="14.[524,628,1481,1512]" captionTargetBox="[286,2110,491,1467]" captionText="FIGURES 4-6.—Xystosomus strigosus Bates, male, from Nova Teutonia, Brazil: 4, maxilla, left side, dorsal aspect; 5, labium, right side, ventral aspect; 6, anterior left leg, posterior aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3828539" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3828539/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Figure 6</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[1283,1399,2036,2072]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Elytra:</emphasis>
As in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1871" box="[1535,1674,2036,2073]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gruti">
<emphasis box="[1535,1564,2036,2073]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">X</emphasis>
. gruti
</taxonomicName>
except all striae evenly 
<emphasis box="[1246,1404,2082,2119]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">impressed</emphasis>
and explanations narrower.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" box="[1284,1834,2129,2166]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[1284,1552,2129,2165]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Microsculpture:</emphasis>
As in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1871" box="[1684,1829,2129,2166]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gruti">
<emphasis box="[1684,1714,2129,2166]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1744,1829,2129,2165]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">gruti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1829,1834,2129,2165]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[1283,1457,2175,2211]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Secondary</emphasis>
sexual 
<emphasis box="[1621,1811,2175,2211]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">characters:</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1844,1928,2175,2212]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Male</emphasis>
genitalia (Figure 26) and female genitalia characteristic 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2073,2105,2221,2258]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">of</emphasis>
the species group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[1284,1467,2313,2350]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Size: Five</emphasis>
specimens: length, 3.5-3.9 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2033,2097,2313,2350]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">mm</emphasis>
; width, 1.6-1.8 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="10" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[1237,2113,1158,2770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">
NATURAL HISTORY.— 
<emphasis box="[1654,1797,2409,2439]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="10">Unknown</emphasis>
, except adults collected in August and September. No teneral specimens seen.
</paragraph>
